      <button class="btn btn-fixed" id="btn-fixed">+1 (Async, Fixed)</button>
      <button class="btn btn-reset" onclick="resetFixed()">↺ Reset</button>

      <div class="log-wrap">
        <div class="log-title">Event Log</div>
        <div class="log" id="fixed-log"></div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div><!-- /panels -->


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
       EXPLANATION CARDS
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="explanation">

    <!-- What is a race condition -->
    <div class="exp-card">
      <h3><span class="badge badge-info">📖 Concept</span> What Is a Race Condition?</h3>
      <p>
        A <strong>race condition</strong> occurs when two or more operations read and write
        a shared resource concurrently, and the final result depends on the unpredictable
        <em>timing</em> of those operations — not on your intended logic.
      </p>
      <p>
        Even though JavaScript is single-threaded, <strong>asynchronous callbacks</strong>
        (setTimeout, fetch, Promises) can all <em>capture</em> the same variable value
        at the same moment, then each write back their own stale copy, silently
        discarding every other update.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Timeline -->
    <div class="exp-card">
      <h3><span class="badge badge-bug">🐛 Bug</span> Step-by-Step Race Condition Timeline</h3>
      <p>
        Imagine you click the button <strong>three times very quickly</strong> before any
        setTimeout fires. Here is exactly what happens:
      </p>

      <div class="timeline">

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=0ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-blue"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert line-blue"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Click #1</strong> — reads <code>count = 0</code>, schedules
            <code>setTimeout(fn, 50)</code>. The callback has captured
            <span class="bad">count = 0</span>.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=10ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-blue"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert line-blue"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Click #2</strong> — reads <code>count = 0</code> (still 0!),
            schedules another callback. It also captured <span class="bad">count = 0</span>.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=20ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-blue"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert line-blue"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Click #3</strong> — reads <code>count = 0</code> again.
            Third callback captures <span class="bad">count = 0</span>.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=50ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-orange"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert line-orange"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Callback #1 fires</strong> — computes <code>0 + 1 = 1</code>,
            writes <code>count = 1</code>. ✓ Correct so far.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=60ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-orange"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert line-orange"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Callback #2 fires</strong> — computes <span class="bad">0 + 1 = 1</span>,
            writes <code>count = 1</code>. ✗ Overwrites the correct value!
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=70ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-red"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert" style="background:transparent"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Callback #3 fires</strong> — computes <span class="bad">0 + 1 = 1</span>,
            writes <code>count = 1</code>. ✗ Three clicks, but count shows
            <span class="bad">1</span> instead of <span class="good">3</span>.
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Code Comparison -->
    <div class="exp-card">
      <h3><span class="badge badge-info">💻 Code</span> Buggy vs Fixed — Side by Side</h3>

      <div class="code-compare">

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-header code-header-bug">🐛 Buggy — stale closure capture</div>
          <pre><span class="hl-comment">// Shared mutable state</span>
<span class="hl-keyword">let</span> <span class="hl-var">count</span> = <span class="hl-number">0</span>;

button.<span class="hl-fn">addEventListener</span>(<span class="hl-string">'click'</span>, () => {
  <span class="hl-comment">// ❌ Read happens NOW (sync)</span>
  <span class="hl-keyword">const</span> <span class="hl-bad">snapshot</span> = <span class="hl-var">count</span>;

  <span class="hl-fn">setTimeout</span>(() => {
    <span class="hl-comment">// ❌ Write uses stale snapshot</span>
    <span class="hl-var">count</span> = <span class="hl-bad">snapshot</span> + <span class="hl-number">1</span>;
    display.<span class="hl-var">textContent</span> = <span class="hl-var">count</span>;
  }, <span class="hl-number">50</span>);
});</pre>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-header code-header-fix">✅ Fixed — read inside the callback</div>
          <pre><span class="hl-comment">// Shared mutable state</span>
<span class="hl-keyword">let</span> <span class="hl-var">count</span> = <span class="hl-number">0</span>;

button.<span class="hl-fn">addEventListener</span>(<span class="hl-string">'click'</span>, () => {
  <span class="hl-comment">// ✅ No read yet — just queue</span>
  <span class="hl-fn">setTimeout</span>(() => {
    <span class="hl-comment">// ✅ Read + write both happen
    //    atomically inside callback</span>
    <span class="hl-var">count</span> = <span class="hl-good">count</span> + <span class="hl-number">1</span>;
    display.<span class="hl-var">textContent</span> = <span class="hl-var">count</span>;
  }, <span class="hl-number">50</span>);
});</pre>
        </div>

      </div>

      <p style="margin-top:16px">
        The key insight: in the buggy version the <strong>read</strong> of
        <code>count</code> happens <em>synchronously</em> at click time, so every
        rapid click captures the <em>same</em> stale value. In the fixed version the
        read is deferred <em>into</em> the callback, so by the time it executes,
        it sees the value that the previous callback already wrote.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Real-world patterns -->
    <div class="exp-card">
      <h3><span class="badge badge-fix">✅ Patterns</span> Real-World Solutions</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>1. Functional updater (React setState):</strong>
        <code>setCount(prev => prev + 1)</code> — React guarantees the callback
        receives the latest state, not a closure-captured snapshot.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>2. Queue / serialise:</strong> Use a Promise chain or an
        async queue so only one update runs at a time.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>3. Debounce / throttle:</strong> Collapse many rapid events
        into one, eliminating the race entirely.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>4. Immutable event sourcing:</strong> Never mutate shared state —
        append events to a log and derive current state by replaying them.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>5. Atomic operations:</strong> In environments with shared memory
        (SharedArrayBuffer + Web Workers), use <code>Atomics.add()</code> for
        true atomic read-modify-write.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div><!-- /explanation -->


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
       JAVASCRIPT
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <script>
    /* ─────────────────────────────────────────
       BUGGY COUNTER
       The read of `buggyCount` happens OUTSIDE
       the setTimeout callback (stale capture).
    ───────────────────────────────────────── */
    let buggyCount  = 0;
    let buggyClicks = 0;

    const buggyDisplay = document.getElementById('buggy-display');
    const buggyShown   = document.getElementById('buggy-shown');
    const buggyClicksEl= document.getElementById('buggy-clicks');
    const buggyLostEl  = document.getElementById('buggy-lost');
    const buggyMsg     = document.getElementById('buggy-msg');
    const buggyLog     = document.getElementById('buggy-log');

    function logBuggy(msg, cls = 'log-entry-info') {
      const el = document.createElement('div');
      el.className = cls;
      el.textContent = `[${new Date().toLocaleTimeString('en',{hour12:false,hour:'2-digit',minute:'2-digit',second:'2-digit'})}] ${msg}`;
      buggyLog.prepend(el);
      // keep log tidy
      while (buggyLog.children.length > 40) buggyLog.removeChild(buggyLog.lastChild);
    }

    function bump(el) {
      el.classList.remove('bump');
      void el.offsetWidth; // reflow
      el.classList.add('bump');
      setTimeout(() => el.classList.remove('bump'), 150);
    }

    document.getElementById('btn-buggy').addEventListener('click', () => {
      buggyClicks++;
      buggyClicksEl.textContent = buggyClicks;

      // ❌ THE BUG: snapshot is captured synchronously right now.
      //    If you click 5 times before any timeout fires, all 5
      //    callbacks will have snapshot = same old value.
      const snapshot = buggyCount;

      logBuggy(`Click #${buggyClicks} — read count=${snapshot} (stale snapshot)`, 'log-entry-info');

      setTimeout(() => {
        buggyCount = snapshot + 1;          // ❌ stale write
        bump(buggyDisplay);
        buggyDisplay.textContent = buggyCount;
        buggyShown.textContent   = buggyCount;

        const lost = buggyClicks - buggyCount;
        buggyLostEl.textContent = lost;
        buggyMsg.textContent = lost > 0
          ? `⚠️ ${lost} update${lost===1?'':'s'} lost!`
          : '✓ No lost updates yet';

        logBuggy(
          `Callback fired → wrote ${snapshot}+1=${buggyCount} | expected=${buggyClicks} | lost=${lost}`,
          lost > 0 ? 'log-entry-bug' : 'log-entry-ok'
        );
      }, 50);
    });

    function resetBuggy() {
      buggyCount = buggyClicks = 0;
      buggyDisplay.textContent = buggyShown.textContent =
        buggyClicksEl.textContent = buggyLostEl.textContent = '0';
      buggyMsg.textContent = '\u00a0';
      buggyLog.innerHTML = '';
      logBuggy('Reset', 'log-entry-info');
    }


    /* ─────────────────────────────────────────
       FIXED COUNTER
       The read of `fixedCount` happens INSIDE
       the setTimeout callback — always fresh.
    ───────────────────────────────────────── */
    let fixedCount  = 0;
    let fixedClicks = 0;

    const fixedDisplay  = document.getElementById('fixed-display');
    const fixedShown    = document.getElementById('fixed-shown');
    const fixedClicksEl = document.getElementById('fixed-clicks');
    const fixedLostEl   = document.getElementById('fixed-lost');
    const fixedMsg      = document.getElementById('fixed-msg');
    const fixedLog      = document.getElementById('fixed-log');

    function logFixed(msg, cls = 'log-entry-info') {
      const el = document.createElement('div');
      el.className = cls;
      el.textContent = `[${new Date().toLocaleTimeString('en',{hour12:false,hour:'2-digit',minute:'2-digit',second:'2-digit'})}] ${msg}`;
      fixedLog.prepend(el);
      while (fixedLog.children.length > 40) fixedLog.removeChild(fixedLog.lastChild);
    }

    document.getElementById('btn-fixed').addEventListener('click', () => {
      fixedClicks++;
      fixedClicksEl.textContent = fixedClicks;

      logFixed(`Click #${fixedClicks} — queued (no read yet)`, 'log-entry-info');

      setTimeout(() => {
        // ✅ THE FIX: read + write both happen here, sequentially.
        //    JS event loop ensures callbacks run one at a time,
        //    so each one sees the result of the previous write.
        fixedCount = fixedCount + 1;       // ✅ fresh read inside callback
        bump(fixedDisplay);
        fixedDisplay.textContent = fixedCount;
        fixedShown.textContent   = fixedCount;

        const lost = fixedClicks - fixedCount;
        fixedLostEl.textContent = lost;
        fixedMsg.textContent = lost === 0
          ? '✓ All updates preserved!'
          : `⚠️ ${lost} lost`;

        logFixed(
          `Callback fired → read+wrote ${fixedCount} | expected=${fixedClicks} | lost=${lost}`,
          lost === 0 ? 'log-entry-ok' : 'log-entry-bug'
        );
      }, 50);
    });

    function resetFixed() {
      fixedCount = fixedClicks = 0;
      fixedDisplay.textContent = fixedShown.textContent =
        fixedClicksEl.textContent = fixedLostEl.textContent = '0';
      fixedMsg.textContent = '\u00a0';
      fixedLog.innerHTML = '';
      logFixed('Reset', 'log-entry-info');
    }
  </script>

</body>
</html>
```

## How to Use It

**Save** the code as `race-condition-demo.html` and open it in any browser.

---

### What You'll See

| Area | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **Left panel (red)** | Buggy async counter — rapid clicks reveal lost updates |
| **Right panel (green)** | Fixed counter — every click is always counted correctly |
| **Event log** | Real-time trace of every read/write so you can watch the race happen |
| **Lost counter** | Shows exactly how many increments were silently discarded |
| **Explanation cards** | Concept, step-by-step timeline, side-by-side code, and real-world fix patterns |

---

### How to Trigger the Bug

1. Click the **red button 5–10 times as fast as possible**
2. Watch **Clicks** jump to e.g. `8` while **Displayed** shows only `3`
3. The **Lost** counter shows the discarded updates
4. Compare with the **green button** — no matter how fast you click, it always matches

---

### The Core Insight

```
BUGGY:  read (now, sync) → wait 50ms → write (stale)
FIXED:  wait 50ms → read + write (both fresh, sequential)
```
Moving the **read inside the callback** means each callback sees the value the previous one already wrote, eliminating the race entirely.

