<!-- ─────────────────────────── EXPLANATION ─────────────────────────── -->
<div class="explanation">
  <h2>🔍 Why Does the Race Condition Happen?</h2>

  <p>
    Both counters use <code>setTimeout</code> to simulate an async operation (like a network request
    or database write). The bug lives in how the <strong>read → modify → write</strong> cycle
    interacts with overlapping async calls.
  </p>

  <div class="steps">
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">1</div>
      <p>
        You click rapidly. Each click <strong>reads</strong> the current value of
        <code>buggyCount</code> — say it's <code>3</code> — and stores it in a local snapshot
        <code>let snap = buggyCount</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">2</div>
      <p>
        Before any <code>setTimeout</code> callback fires, you click again. That second click
        <em>also</em> reads <code>buggyCount = 3</code> (still unchanged!) and stores
        <code>snap = 3</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">3</div>
      <p>
        The first callback fires: <code>buggyCount = snap + 1 = 4</code>. ✓ Correct so far.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">4</div>
      <p>
        The second callback fires: <code>buggyCount = snap + 1 = 4</code> again! 🔥
        The second click's work is <strong>completely lost</strong> — both increments
        produced the same result.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    This is the classic <strong>read-modify-write race</strong>: multiple operations each
    capture a stale snapshot of shared state, then all write back a value derived from that
    same stale snapshot, so only one increment "survives".
  </p>

  <div class="fix-box">
    <h3>✅ The Fix: Never Snapshot — Always Increment Atomically</h3>
    <p>
      The fixed version does <code>fixedCount++</code> <em>synchronously</em> at click time,
      before the async delay. The async callback only handles side-effects (like updating the UI
      or confirming a server write) — it never re-reads or re-writes the shared counter.
      Because the increment happens in the synchronous click handler, JavaScript's single-threaded
      event loop guarantees no two increments can interleave.
    </p>
  </div>
