## What's Going On

### The Bug (Left Panel — Red)
The buggy `increment` function follows this flawed pattern:
1. **Read** → `const snap = buggyCount` (captures current value)
2. **Wait** → `setTimeout(..., randomDelay)` — async gap opens here
3. **Write** → `buggyCount = snap + 1` (writes stale snapshot + 1)

When you click rapidly, **many calls all read the same stale `snap`** before any callback fires. Every callback then writes `snap + 1` — the same value — so only one increment survives no matter how many times you clicked.

### The Fix (Right Panel — Green)
The fix moves the increment **before** the async gap:
```js
fixedCount++;              // ← synchronous, atomic, safe
const committed = fixedCount;
setTimeout(() => {
  display(committed);      // ← only UI work in the callback
}, delay);
```
Because JavaScript is single-threaded, the synchronous `fixedCount++` can never be interleaved with another click's increment — each click gets its own exclusive increment before yielding to the event loop.

