  <h2>📖 Why Does the Race Condition Happen?</h2>

  <p>
    JavaScript is single-threaded, but <strong>asynchronous callbacks</strong> scheduled with
    <code>setTimeout</code> (or Promises, fetch, etc.) can still create race conditions
    when they share mutable state.
  </p>

  <p>Here is exactly what goes wrong in the <strong>buggy version</strong> when you click three times quickly:</p>

  <ul class="step-list">
    <li>🔵 <strong>Click 1</strong> — reads <code>count = 0</code>, stores it in local <code>val = 0</code>, schedules callback A</li>
    <li>🔵 <strong>Click 2</strong> — reads <code>count = 0</code> (still 0!), stores <code>val = 0</code>, schedules callback B</li>
    <li>🔴 <strong>Callback A fires</strong> — writes <code>count = val + 1 = 1</code> ✓</li>
    <li>🔴 <strong>Callback B fires</strong> — writes <code>count = val + 1 = 1</code> ✗ (should be 2!)</li>
    <li>🟢 <strong>Result</strong> — 2 clicks happened but count is only <strong>1</strong>. One update was silently lost.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The root cause is the <strong>read → delay → write</strong> pattern.
    The local snapshot <code>val</code> becomes <em>stale</em> the moment
    any other callback writes to <code>count</code> before this one runs.
  </p>

  <div class="highlight-box">
    <h3>🔧 The Fix</h3>
    <p>
      The fixed version never snapshots <code>count</code> at click time.
      Instead, the <code>setTimeout</code> callback reads and writes
      <code>count</code> atomically at the moment it actually executes —
      so it always sees the most up-to-date value and no updates are lost.
      In frameworks like React, this maps directly to using the
      <code>setState(prev => prev + 1)</code> functional form instead of
      <code>setState(count + 1)</code>.
    </p>
  </div>
