      <p>
        Each click schedules an async operation that <strong>reads</strong> the
        current count, waits, then <strong>writes</strong> count + 1. When
        multiple clicks fire before any write completes, they all read the
        <em>same stale value</em> and each writes the same result — losing
        all but one update.
      </p>
      <div class="code-block">
<span class="cm">// ❌ BUGGY: classic read-modify-write race</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">increment</span>() {
  <span class="hl">  <span class="kw">const</span> snapshot = count; <span class="cm">// read stale value</span></span>
  <span class="fn">setTimeout</span>(() => {
    <span class="cm">  // other increments may have</span>
    <span class="cm">  // already run here — snapshot</span>
    <span class="cm">  // is now stale!</span>
    <span class="hl">    count = snapshot + <span class="num">1</span>; <span class="cm">// overwrites!</span></span>
    render(count);
  }, delay);
}
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="exp-box fix-box">
      <h3>✅ THE FIX — Serialized Queue</h3>
      <p>
        Instead of reading the value at click-time, we push work into a
        <strong>queue</strong> and process items one-at-a-time. Each item
        reads the count only when it's its turn to run, so no two operations
        ever overlap on the same value.
      </p>
