  <h2>🔍 Why Does This Break?</h2>

  <p>
    JavaScript is single-threaded, but <strong>asynchronous operations create interleaving</strong>.
    When you use <code>setTimeout</code> (or any async mechanism), the engine suspends that
    task and runs others before coming back. This produces a classic
    <strong>read–modify–write race condition</strong>.
  </p>

  <h3>The Buggy Pattern <span class="tag bug">BUG</span></h3>
  <pre><span class="cm">// Shared state</span>
<span class="kw">let</span> counter = <span class="num">0</span>;

<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">buggyIncrement</span>() {
<span class="bad-line">  <span class="kw">const</span> current = counter;          <span class="cm">// 1. READ  — captures value NOW</span></span>
  <span class="fn">setTimeout</span>(() => {
<span class="bad-line">    counter = current + <span class="num">1</span>;           <span class="cm">// 2. WRITE — uses the stale snapshot</span></span>
  }, <span class="fn">Math</span>.random() * <span class="num">80</span>);
}</pre>

  <h3>The Race — Step by Step</h3>
  <ol class="race-steps">
    <li>Call #1 fires. It reads <code>counter = 0</code> and stores it in <code>current₁ = 0</code>.</li>
    <li>Call #2 fires immediately after. It also reads <code>counter = 0</code> → <code>current₂ = 0</code>.</li>
    <li>…calls #3 through #10 all do the same. They all captured <strong>0</strong>.</li>
    <li>Timeouts begin resolving. Call #1 writes <code>counter = 0 + 1 = 1</code>. ✓</li>
    <li>Call #2 writes <code>counter = 0 + 1 = 1</code>. It <strong>overwrites</strong> call #1's result.</li>
    <li>All 10 calls write <strong>1</strong>. Final value: <strong>1</strong> instead of <strong>10</strong>.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>The Fixed Pattern <span class="tag fix">FIX</span></h3>
  <pre><span class="kw">let</span> counter = <span class="num">0</span>;

<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">fixedIncrement</span>() {
  <span class="cm">// No local snapshot taken here</span>
  <span class="fn">setTimeout</span>(() => {
<span class="good-line">    counter = counter + <span class="num">1</span>;            <span class="cm">// READ + WRITE happen together at callback time</span></span>
  }, <span class="fn">Math</span>.random() * <span class="num">80</span>);
}</pre>

  <p>
    Because JavaScript callbacks execute on the <strong>single-threaded event loop</strong>,
    each callback runs to completion before the next one starts.
    Reading and writing <code>counter</code> inside the same callback is therefore
    <strong>atomic with respect to other callbacks</strong> — no other callback can
    sneak in between the read and the write.
  </p>

  <h3>The Key Insight</h3>
  <p>
    The bug is not about <em>when</em> the write happens — it's about
    <strong>which value is being written</strong>.
    Capturing state into a local variable before an async gap means you're
    scheduling a write of <em>yesterday's truth</em>.
    The fix keeps the read inside the callback so it always sees
    <em>today's truth</em> at the moment of execution.
  </p>

  <h3>Real-World Equivalents</h3>
  <p>
    This same pattern destroys correctness in: React <code>setState</code> calls
    that close over stale state (fix: use the updater form <code>setState(prev => prev + 1)</code>),
    database read-modify-write without transactions, and multi-threaded code
    without locks. The shape of the bug is always identical.
  </p>
</div>

